Bounties are created whenever someone requests inference on a chute that is cold. This can be from new chutes being deployed, a chute going cold because miners de-allocated them, a change to an existing chute, etc. In this case, if memory servers, there were several deployments of the deepseek-r1 model to test various methods from the deepseek-ai open source week and other changes that were incorporated into sglang/vllm.  If I deploy the model say 10 times, that would be 10 different bounties created. If some of those changes are unstable and cause crashes from say OOM errors, then it could create more, etc.
That said, outside of changes to existing chutes, bounties are very rare right now because of the excess inventory. We have many times more hardware than required to run all chutes.
Additionally, any time a large miner has downtime, huge variations in score can occur when that downtime shifts out of the scoring window. See incentives for some of the top miners at >= 0.1. If 10% of the inventory goes offline, even for a few hours, that's a lot of abrupt shifting in invocation counts, compute time, and theoretically bounties.

large changes in usage hour over hour
```sql
chutes=> WITH hourly_metrics AS (
  SELECT 
    chute_id,
    to_char(started_at, 'YYYY-MM-DD HH24:00:00') as hour,
    count(distinct(parent_invocation_id)) as total_count,
    sum(extract(epoch from completed_at - started_at)) as invocation_seconds,
    sum((metrics->>'it')::integer + (metrics->>'ot')::integer) as token_count
  FROM invocations 
  WHERE started_at >= now() - interval '9 days'
  GROUP BY chute_id, hour
  ORDER BY hour DESC
),
hourly_changes AS (
  SELECT 
    current.chute_id,
    current.hour,
    current.total_count,
    current.invocation_seconds,
    current.token_count,
    LAG(current.total_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) as prev_count,
    LAG(current.invocation_seconds) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) as prev_seconds,
    LAG(current.token_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) as prev_tokens,
    CASE 
      WHEN LAG(current.total_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) > 0 
      THEN (current.total_count - LAG(current.total_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)) * 100.0 / 
           LAG(current.total_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)
      ELSE NULL
    END as count_pct_change,
    CASE 
      WHEN LAG(current.invocation_seconds) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) > 0 
      THEN (current.invocation_seconds - LAG(current.invocation_seconds) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)) * 100.0 / 
           LAG(current.invocation_seconds) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)
      ELSE NULL
    END as seconds_pct_change,
    CASE 
      WHEN LAG(current.token_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour) > 0 
      THEN (current.token_count - LAG(current.token_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)) * 100.0 / 
           LAG(current.token_count) OVER (PARTITION BY current.chute_id ORDER BY current.hour)
      ELSE NULL
    END as tokens_pct_change
  FROM hourly_metrics current
)
SELECT *
FROM hourly_changes
WHERE 
  (ABS(count_pct_change) > 50 and prev_count >= 1000) OR 
  (ABS(seconds_pct_change) > 50 and prev_count >= 1000) OR
  (ABS(tokens_pct_change) > 50 and prev_count >= 1000)
ORDER BY count_pct_change DESC, chute_id limit 10;
```

Yeah basically same plan we have (and good for agent platform to prove it was not a human). TEE can provide hardware based proof of encryption/privacy and can be used to sign the software being run, etc. Our main problem is that currently the vast majority of GPU providers don't enable the various TEE-required BIOS options since they like having observability into the instances (most use VM-based deployments), and actually CPU/RAM can have this mechanism but not necessarily the GPU, for the GPU to have full isolation requires nvidia confidential computing, which is only supported on hopper and blackwell GPUs, and the current version of nvidia CC (last time I checked anyways) can only do single device passthrough so it's actually a bit of a nightmare to try doing multi-gpu inference in a completely secure way.

I think part of the problem is the cost of the hardware. TEE on GPU is only supported on the latest gen CPUs most of the cloud providers provide the lowest CPU needed to reasonably complete the task since users only pay per hour for the GPU, and very few look at the cpu model and out of the ones that do care about cpu, few are willing to pay more for the better/newer CPUs.

I think we can do a phased rollout though, requiring the CPU tee modules first (sgx/tdx/sev) which most modern CPUs do actually support, it's just disabled by most providers in the bios to collect more info and otherwise snoop on tenants. NVidia CC is a separate matter in a way, in that with just CPU TEE with can sign and verify the software is running what is claimed, and from that we can prove that prompt logging is disabled for example (and all network traffic is encrypted, RAM encrypted, etc.)

If we get that level of security, without nvidia CC, it would require a fairly sophisticated attacker to actually get meaningful information out of it. VRAM is a fairly wide range of values, all just floating point matrices, so you'd have to map VRAM to model weights vs KV cache, differentiate which parts of that are actually associated with a single prompt, manage to capture it such that it's all coherent and part of a single prompt, decode into the actual text, etc.  It's possible, but really more trouble than it's worth to actually try to capture data from vram I think.

So let's get TEE on the CPU with encrypted RAM first, prove the software is correct, then we can figure out the nvidia side of things when that ecosystem has evolved a bit and is more friendly with all of the rest of the components.

Basically each chute will have a capped capacity (and a minimum size for auto-scaling down, miners can of course scale down to zero), and that capped capacity will be based on utilization.  The "busy_ratio" compares the amount of time requests were in-flight to the amount of time the instances were online. The utilization time can actually exceed online time because of concurrency.  Whenever a chute falls below 30% utilization, the max capacity is decreased, and the "worst" instance is ejected. When the capacity has reached a stable point, there will be a queue size where miners can be in line to be next to receive a slot. Periodically the worst instance is ejected and first instance in the queue is allowed to be admitted.

```py
def find_orphan_remote_gpus(local_inventory: list[LocalInventoryItem], remote_inventory: list[RemoteInventoryItem]) -> list[RemoteInventoryItem]:
    """
    Find orphaned remote GPUs that are not present in the local inventory but are still stuck in the remote inventory.
    This means that the Chutes validator thinks we still have those cGPUs but we don't have them in our local inventory.
    """
    local_gpu_ids = set()
    remote_gpu_ids = set()

    orphaned_remote_gpus: list[RemoteInventoryItem] = []

    for server in local_inventory:
        for local_gpu in server["gpus"]:
            local_gpu_ids.add(local_gpu["gpu_id"])

    for remote_gpu in remote_inventory:
        remote_gpu_ids.add(remote_gpu["uuid"])

    stuck_ids = remote_gpu_ids - local_gpu_ids

    orphaned_remote_gpus = [gpu for gpu in remote_inventory if gpu["uuid"] in stuck_ids]

    return orphaned_remote_gpus
```

You can mostly ignore the current PR that is up, as it's not really the best approach - the one caveat is the change to the unique chute count (based on average number of active chutes at intervals, that will be the same).

What I'm trying to do now is basically dynamically and continuously calculate the maximum number of instances for chutes based on performance with varying levels of concurrency (i.e. we can increase concurrency/decrease instance counts until we have a noticeable performance hit then we need to stop scaling down), which we can calculate by the same metrics used for our least_conn style connection manager, in conjuction with stats on how often miners return a 429 error (if miners hit capacity then obviously we need to scale up).

The utilization score will be based on GPUs in the miners' inventory (regardless of being tied to an instance or not) compared to utilization, and will be weighted by the compute units for each (e.g. a very low utilization on a chute that requires a single 3090 won't affect your score that much if you also have an 8x h200 with heavy utilization).
